\begin{align*}
BP^2 &= AB^2 + AP^2 - 2 \cdot AB \cdot AP \cdot \cos 45^\circ \\
&= c^2 + 1 - c \sqrt{2}.
\end{align*}By the Law of Cosines on triangle $CBP$,
\[a^2 = BP^2 + CP^2 - 2 \cdot BP \cdot CP \cdot \cos \angle BPC.\]Since $\angle BPC = 135^\circ$, and $\cos 135^\circ = -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},$
\begin{align*}
a^2 &= BP^2 + CP^2 + BP \cdot CP \\
&= c^2 + 1 - c \sqrt{2} + 4 + 2c - 3c \sqrt{2} \\
&= 5 + (1 - 4 \sqrt{2})c.
\end{align*}Then
\begin{align*}
b^2 &= c^2 - a^2 \\
&= c^2 - (5 + (1 - 4 \sqrt{2})c) \\
&= (3 - 4 \sqrt{2})c - 5.
\end{align*}Then the area of triangle $ABC$ is
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2} ab &= \frac{1}{2} c \sqrt{(3 - 4 \sqrt{2})c - 5} \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \sqrt{5c^2 - 8c^3 + 16c^2 \sqrt{2}} - \frac{5c}{2} \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \sqrt{5(c^2 - 2c + 4) + 8(c - 2)^2} - \frac{5c}{2} \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \sqrt{5(a^2 + b^2) + 8(c - 2)^2} - \frac{5c}{2} \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \sqrt{5(5 + (1 - 4 \sqrt{2})c) + 8(c - 2)^2} - \frac{5c}{2}.
\end{align*}From $c^2 = a^2 + b^2,$ $c^2 - 2c + 4 = a^2 + b^2 - 2c + 4 = a^2 + (c - b)^2 + 4,$ so
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2} \sqrt{5(5 + (1 - 4 \sqrt{2})c) + 8(c - 2)^2} - \frac{5c}{2} &= \frac{1}{2} \sqrt{5a^2 + 5(c - b)^2 + 40} - \frac{5c}{2} \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \sqrt{5a^2 + 5b^2 + 40} - \frac{5c}{2}.
\end{align*}By Pythagoras, $a^2 + b^2 = c^2 = 5 + 2 \sqrt{2},$ so
\[\frac{1}{2} \sqrt{5a^2 + 5b^2 + 40} - \frac{5c}{2} = \boxed{\sqrt{10 + 4 \sqrt{2}} - 5 \sqrt{2}}.\]

