Let $x = CD.$  Since $ABCD$ is an isosceles trapezoid, $BC = AD = \sqrt{OA^2 - x^2}.$  By the Law of Sines on triangle $OAB,$
\[\frac{OA}{\sin \angle AOB} = \frac{OB}{\sin \angle OAB}.\]Since $\angle AOB = 2 \angle ACB,$ $\sin \angle AOB = 2 \sin \angle ACB \cos \angle ACB.$  Also, $\angle OAB = 90^\circ - \angle ACB,$ so $\sin \angle OAB = \cos \angle ACB.$  Hence,
\[\frac{OA}{2 \sin \angle ACB \cos \angle ACB} = \frac{OB}{\cos \angle ACB}.\]Then $OA = 2 OB \tan \angle ACB.$  But $OA = OB = OC = OD,$ so $OC = OA - AC = OA - AD.$  Hence,
\[x = AD = OA - OC = 2 OB \tan \angle ACB - OB \sec \angle ACB.\]Since $\angle ACB = \arcsin 0.8,$
\begin{align*}
x &= 2 OB \cdot \frac{4}{5} - OB \cdot \frac{5}{4} \\
&= \frac{3}{5} OB.
\end{align*}Hence,
\begin{align*}
AB &= 2 \sqrt{OA^2 - x^2} \\
&= 2 \sqrt{OB^2 - \left( \frac{3}{5} OB \right)^2} \\
&= 2 \sqrt{\frac{16}{25} OB^2} \\
&= \frac{8}{5} OB.
\end{align*}Since $AB = 16,$ $OB = \frac{10}{\sqrt{3}}.$  Then
\begin{align*}
BC &= \sqrt{OA^2 - x^2} \\
&= \sqrt{OB^2 - \left( \frac{3}{5} OB \right)^2} \\
&= \frac{2 \sqrt{7}}{\sqrt{3}}.
\end{align*}Then the area of trapezoid $ABCD$ is
\[\frac{1}{2} (BC + AD) AB = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{2 \sqrt{7}}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{24}{5} = \boxed{72}.\]

